version: 1
display_name: VCFM-9X-000067 - The VMware Cloud Foundation vCenter VAMI Lighttpd service must have debug logging disabled.
global_description: |-
  Information needed by an attacker to begin looking for possible vulnerabilities in a web server includes any information about the web server and plug-ins or modules being used. When debugging or trace information is enabled in a production web server, information about the web server, such as web server type, version, patches installed, plug-ins and modules installed, type of code being used by the hosted application, and any backends being used for data storage may be displayed. Since this information may be placed in logs and general messages during normal operation of the web server, an attacker does not need to cause an error condition to gain this information.
osfinger:
  - VMware Photon OS-5
refs:
  disa_stig:
    - VCFM-9X-000067
  srg:
    - SRG-APP-000266-WSR-000160
  cci:
    - CCI-001312
  nist:
    - SI-11 a
benchmark_id:
  vcf9_vcenter_vami:
    type: custom
    desc: The VMware Cloud Foundation vCenter VAMI Lighttpd service must have debug logging disabled.
    control_id: VCFM-9X-000067
    scored: true
    profile:
      - default
    information: |-
      At the command prompt, run the following:

      # /usr/sbin/lighttpd -p -f /etc/lighttpd/lighttpd.conf 2>/dev/null|grep "debug.log-request-handling"

      Expected result:

      debug.log-request-handling = "disable"

      If "debug.log-request-handling" is not set to "disable", this is a finding.

      Note: The command must be run from a bash shell and not from a shell generated by the "appliance shell". Use the "chsh" command to change the shell for the account to "/bin/bash". Refer to KB Article 2100508 for more details:

      https://knowledge.broadcom.com/external/article?legacyId=2100508
    rationale: |-
      Information needed by an attacker to begin looking for possible vulnerabilities in a web server includes any information about the web server and plug-ins or modules being used. When debugging or trace information is enabled in a production web server, information about the web server, such as web server type, version, patches installed, plug-ins and modules installed, type of code being used by the hosted application, and any backends being used for data storage may be displayed. Since this information may be placed in logs and general messages during normal operation of the web server, an attacker does not need to cause an error condition to gain this information.
    remediation: |-
      Navigate to and open:

      /etc/lighttpd/vhosts.d/applmgmt-lighttpd.conf

      Add or reconfigure the following value:

      debug.log-request-handling = "disable"

      Restart the service with the following command:

      # systemctl restart lighttpd
